The data obtained from the Yelp Dataset Challenge will only be used for JSC270 Course project. I am permitted use these data to create statistical summaries and visualizations in electronic form. I don't have the permission to publicly display these data set or use them for any commercial purposes. 1.2. Data summary¶

The data is stored in 5 tables. Each of them stores the following information.(1)

Business¶

Give all information about businesses on Yelp and stores. Each line gives information about one business

  • Referenced by business-id
  • Address (actual address, city, latitude, longitude, postal code, state),
  • Name of the store
  • Number of reviews
  • Rating stars
  • Categories that classify the business
  • Attributes: a nested dictionary that stores the different aspects of the restaurant.

Checkin¶

Give the checkin date time of businesses. Each line gives information about one business

  • business-id: reference to the business being checked in
  • date: a list of datetime, separated by comma

Review¶

Give all reviews and rating made by a user. Each line gives information about one review

  • referenced by review-id
  • business-id: reference to the business being reviewed
  • cool, funny, useful: number of users that rate this comment as cool, funny, or useful, respectively.
  • stars: the integer variable scaled from 0-5 representing the rating
  • text: the content of the review
  • user-id: reference to the user wrote the review
  • date: the date of the review posting

Tip¶

Give all tips (key information about a business). Each line gives information about one tip

  • business-id: reference to the business being tipped
  • compliment-count: the count of compliments by other users
  • date: the date of the tip posting
  • text: the content of the tip
  • user-id: reference to the user wrote the tip

User¶

Give all information about users. Each line gives information about one user.

  • reference by user-id
  • average_stars: average of rating stars given by the user
  • complement: there are 11 types of complements, and each stores the count of compliments in that type given by other users.
  • cool, funny, useful: the counts of cool, funny, useful given by other users
  • elite: the years when the user is an elite of Yelp
  • fans: the number of fans
  • friends: a list of user-id referred to the friends of the user
  • name: the name of the user
  • review_count: the total number of reviews written by the user
  • yelping_since: the datetime start being a Yelp user.

# load the business from Yelp dataset
business = pd.read_json(root+"/yelp_dataset~/business.json", lines=True, encoding="utf_8")


def clean(row):
    
    # clean categories
    error_words = ['& Probates', 'Wine & Spirits', 'Trusts', 'Mags',
                   'Music & Video', 'Vintage & Consignment']
    error_dicts = {'Wills': 'Wills, Trusts, & Probates',
                   'Beer': 'Beer, Wine & Spirits',
                   'Books': 'Books, Mags, Music & Video',
                   'Dry Cleaning & Laundry': 'Dry Cleaning',
                   'Flowers': 'Flowers & Gifts',
                   'Golf Equipment Shops': 'Golf Equipment',
                   'Used': 'Used, Vintage & Consignment'}
    row['categories'] = row['categories'].split(", ") if row['categories'] else []
    i = 0
    while i < len(row['categories']):
        if row['categories'][i] in error_dicts.keys():
            row['categories'][i] = error_dicts[row['categories'][i]]
        if row['categories'][i] in error_words:
            row['categories'].pop(i)
            i -= 1
        i += 1
        
    return row
business = business.apply(clean, axis=1)

# use longitude and latitude to create geo Point
business['coordinates'] = list(zip(business['longitude'], business['latitude']))
business['coordinates'] = business['coordinates'].apply(Point)
business = business.drop(['longitude', 'latitude'], axis=1)

There are about 200,000 business in the U.S. and Canada in this dataset.

2.2 What are the most frequent business categories overall¶

Investigation¶

Each business in the dataset is categorized by several key words. In addition, I found the category listing of Yelp's ALL Category List (6). Indicated in the category list, each category has a parent attribute and the root categories have empty parent attribute. The categories are managed in a tree-shaped relationship. Therefore, I plot the number of business in each root category (categories without parent category) to examine the distribution of business categories.

In [9]:
# create a category dataframe for reference, 
category_dict = {}

with urlopen("https://www.yelp.com/developers/documentation/v3/all_category_list/categories.json") as url:
    categories = json.loads(url.read().decode())
    
for item in categories:
    category_dict[item['alias']] =  {'parents': item['parents'], 'category': item['title'], 'level': -1}

# add ethnic food category since it appears in our dataset but not in category list
category_dict['ethnicfood'] = {'parents': ['food'], 'category': 'Ethnic Food', 'level': -1}

# make the level based on the depth of the category in the category tree
def update_level(name):
    if category_dict[name]['level'] != -1:
        return
    elif not category_dict[name]['parents']:
        category_dict[name]['level'] = 0
    else:
        max_level = 0
        for p in category_dict[name]['parents']:
            update_level(p)
        for p in category_dict[name]['parents']:
            if max_level < category_dict[p]['level'] + 1:
                max_level = 1 + category_dict[p]['level']
        category_dict[name]['level'] = max_level

for key, value in category_dict.items():
    update_level(key)

# make the category list into a dataframe
category_df = {'category': [], 'parent': [], 'level': []}
for key, value in category_dict.items():
    category_df['category'].append(value['category'])
    category_df['level'].append(value['level'])
    parents = [category_dict[i]['category'] for i in value['parents']]
    category_df['parent'].append(parents)
category_df = pd.DataFrame(category_df)

# count all categories
all_categories = []
for row in list(business['categories']):
    all_categories += row
all_categories = pd.DataFrame(all_categories)
all_categories.columns = ['category']
allbusiness_category = all_categories.merge(category_df, on="category", how="inner")
category_count = allbusiness_category.groupby('category').first() 
category_count['count'] = allbusiness_category.groupby('category').count()['level']
category_count = category_count.reset_index()

Discussion and Further research¶

An interesting observation from the categories is that there are many overlapping such as "Food" and "Restaurant". The many overlapping categories are important for the business owners to best describe their business, while it may cause trouble when investigating the proportions of different categories of business. Therefore, further investigation can be performed on the relations and correlations among these categories. A a more concise categorization can be proposed to group business.

In [16]:
# contingency test
z, p, df, expected = sp.stats.chi2_contingency([bike_category_count['count_bike'], 
                                                bike_category_count['count_no_info'],
                                                bike_category_count['count_no_bike']])
# print("test statistic: ", z)
# print("p-value: ", p)

From the proportion plot, we notice that there are significant differences among the proportions for different categories.

Then, I performed chi square contingency test. The null hypothesis is that having bike parking is independent on the category of the business, and the alternative hypothesis is that having bike parking is dependent on the category of the business. The test statistic is 94046, the distribution of the test statistic follows $\chi^2_{40}$ and p-value is 0.0. The extreme small p-value gives strong evidence that having bike parking is dependent on the category of the business.

From the observations, food and nightlife are most likely to have bike parking.

Conclusion¶

There is some evidence that the business location and the likelihood of having bike parking are independent. On the other hand, there are strong evidence of a relationship between the category of the business and the likelihood of having bike parking. Food, nightlife, and Beauty&Spa have the highest proportion of having bike parking.

Discussion and Further research¶

Consider the categories with extremely large proportion of lacking bike parking information, namely financial services, pets, and religious organizations. The numbers of business in such categories are significantly smaller than those with smaller proportion of lack bike parking information. Further research may look at whether the popularity of the business category is related to the proportion of business that misses no descriptive attributes (such as bike parking).

Conclusion¶

Although the question asks whether more yelp reviews lead to a higher rating, I cannot draw any conclusion about the causation without further information. I can only state that there is a correlation between the two variables. From all the statistical summaries, there is a relationship between the number of yelp reviews and the rating. Overall there is no evidence that the relationship is positive. Instead, the number of reviews is higher when the rating is closer to 4.0.

Discussion¶

I notice that the average rating of all reviews on Yelp is about 3.7. The correlation may not be meaningful because the user might just be more likely to give a rating of 4, and it is not related to how popular the business is.

Conclusion¶

Discussion and further analysis¶

Notice that the categories are not independent of each other, hence the proportion of each category is influenced by correlation.

Also, I'm interested whether Toronto actually favors more about restaurants, food, and nightlife compared to other metropolitan area. Alternatively, whether Yelp service focus more on the restaurant in GTA, even Canada, than in the U.S.

how does business location influence the rating¶

In [35]:

Finding mean review count of each area is insignificant: the business that have plenty of reviews has too much influence on the mean. Also, I'm more interested in whether the location is associated with the "popular" business.

Therefore, I propose that the "popular" business are those have more reviews than 44 reviews and the rest are "unpopular". 44 is from the boxplot whiskers, and we can obtain the business that are far more popular with this categorization.

Then, I can calculate the proportion of popular business in each neighborhood, and color the neighborhood on the plot.

In [36]:
toronto_business_area_count_popular = toronto_business_area.loc[toronto_business_area["review_count"] > 44].groupby("AREA_NAME").count()[["business_id"]].reset_index()
toronto_business_area_count_popular.columns = ['area', 'popular']

toronto_business_area_count.columns = ['area', 'count']

toronto_business_area_count['proportion'] = toronto_business_area_count['popular'] / toronto_business_area_count['count']
toronto_business_area_count = toronto_business_area_count.merge(toronto_business_area.groupby("AREA_NAME").first()[['geometry']], how="left", left_on="area", right_on="AREA_NAME")

ax.set_title("The proportion of popular business in each neighborhood")
ax.set_axis_off();

I don't observe any obvious pattern on the influence of business location that influence the proportion of popular business.

Conclusion¶

There is evidence that business location and reviews are related. The business location plays an important role in review ratings. Specifically, the closer to the lake shore is correlated with the higher rating. However, there is no obvious pattern between the business location and the proportion of business with more reviews.

4.4. Is it true that for every Tim Hortons in the GTA there is a Starbucks nearby?¶

In [37]:

Investigation¶

First, I calculate the closest Starbucks for each Tim Horton's location and access the distribution of the distance. I plot all the Starbucks and Tim Horton's on GTA map, along with the line connecting each Tim Horton's and its closet Starbucks.

In [38]:
# calculate the distance from Tim Hortons to the closest business
business_tag = ['starbucks', 'mcdonald', 'secondcup', 'shoppers']
dis_tim = gta_tims[['coordinates']].copy()
dis_tim.columns = ['tim_cor']
for tag in business_tag:
    tag_uu = gta_business.loc[[tag in name for name in business_names_processed]].unary_union
    dis_tim[tag + '_cor'] = [shapely.ops.nearest_points(cor, tag_uu)[1] for cor in dis_tim['tim_cor']]
    dis_tim[tag + '_line'] = [shapely.geometry.LineString([dis_tim['tim_cor'].values[i],
                                                           dis_tim[tag + '_cor'].values[i]]) for i in range(len(dis_tim))]
    distance = []
    for i in range(len(dis_tim)):
        p1 = (dis_tim[tag + '_cor'].values[i].x, 
              dis_tim[tag + '_cor'].values[i].y)
        p2 = (dis_tim['tim_cor'].values[i].x, 
              dis_tim['tim_cor'].values[i].y)
        distance.append(geodesic(p1, p2).km)
    dis_tim[tag + '_distance'] = distance
    
# plot the distance
ax = canada_mpa.loc[canada_mpa['name'] == "Toronto"].plot(alpha=0.2, figsize=(12,8))
gta_starbucks.plot(color="#067655", ax=ax, markersize=2, alpha=0.5)
gta_tims.plot(color="#dc0f2d", ax=ax, markersize=2, alpha=0.5)
ax.set_axis_off()
ax.set_title("The locations of Starbucks and Tim Horton's in GTA")
ax.legend(["Starbucks", "Tim Hortons"]);
gpd.GeoDataFrame(dis_tim[['starbucks_line']], geometry='starbucks_line').plot(color='orange', alpha=0.5, ax=ax);

I extract all the noun phrases, since they contributes to the majority of a text's meaning. I do a word count on the extracted phrases. I remove phrases thats related to the business brand itself, since they are highly dependent on the brand the reviewer went. Note that this means there's no phrase like "Starbucks" in Starbucks' reviews but "Tim Horton's" will still exist in Starbucks' reviews.

In [43]:
# nltk.download('brown')

# tokenize reviews and count all noun phrases
np_counts = []
np_tokens = []
for row in gta_ts_review['text']:
    np_counts.append(Counter(TextBlob(row).np_counts))
    np_tokens.append(TextBlob(row).tokenize())
gta_ts_review['np_counts'] = np_counts
gta_ts_review['np_tokens'] = np_tokens

# create a word counter by summing up the count in each review
word_counter_tims = Counter()
word_counter_star = Counter()
word_counter_sc = Counter()
for c in gta_ts_review.loc[gta_ts_review['name'] == 'Tims']['np_counts']:
    word_counter_tims += c
for c in gta_ts_review.loc[gta_ts_review['name'] == 'Starbucks']['np_counts']:
    word_counter_star += c
for c in gta_ts_review.loc[gta_ts_review['name'] == 'second cup']['np_counts']:
    word_counter_sc += c
    
# remove self-referential phrases
word_count_tims_df = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(word_counter_tims, orient="index", columns =['count']).reset_index()
word_count_tims_df = word_count_tims_df[['tim' not in word or 'time' in word for word in word_count_tims_df['index']]]
word_count_tims_df['proportion'] = np.round(word_count_tims_df['count'] / word_count_tims_df['count'].sum(), 4)

word_count_star_df = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(word_counter_star, orient="index", columns =['count']).reset_index()
word_count_star_df = word_count_star_df[['starbucks' not in word for word in word_count_star_df['index']]]
word_count_star_df['proportion'] = np.round(word_count_star_df['count'] / word_count_star_df['count'].sum(), 4)

word_count_sc_df = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(word_counter_sc, orient="index", columns =['count']).reset_index()
word_count_sc_df = word_count_sc_df[['second cup' not in word for word in word_count_sc_df['index']]]
word_count_sc_df['proportion'] = np.round(word_count_sc_df['count'] / word_count_sc_df['count'].sum(), 4)

    review_frequencies[phrases[i]] = count[i]

\begin{center}The 10 most frequent phrases for each business\\ \begin{tabular}{llll} \toprule index & Tims rank & Starbucks rank & Second Cup rank \\ \midrule canada & 1 & & \\ toronto & 2 & 3 & 2 \\ starbucks & 3 & & 1 \\ ca n't & 4 & 2 & 8 \\ coffee & 5 & & 4 \\ customer service & 6 & 5 & \\ staff & 7 & 1 & \\ wendy & 8 & & \\ wifi & 9 & 6 & 9 \\ overall & 10 & 7 & \\ nice & & 4 & 5 \\ love & & 8 & \\ great place & & 9 & \\ great location & & 10 & \\ coffee shop & & & 3 \\ cup location & & & 6 \\ hot chocolate & & & 7 \\ free wifi & & & 10 \\ \bottomrule \end{tabular} \end{center}

"Toronto", "can't", and "wifi" appear in all three cases. Also, Tim Horton's and Starbucks have 6 phrases, Tim Horton's and Second Cup share only 5 phrases, Starbucks and Second Cup share 4 phrases. Overall, reviews on Tim Horton's and Starbucks share more similarities compares to reviews on Second Cup.

ALso, a very interesting observation is that reviews on both Tim Horton's and Second Cup mentioned "Starbucks" frequently, while no reviews on Starbucks mentioned "Tims" or "Second Cup". Also, Starbucks reviewers have more positive phrases such as "nice", "love", "great place", and "great location". Therefore, I did a sentiment test to evaluate their polarity of each review. Polarity is a measurement between [-1, 1], from -1 being the most negative to 1 being the most positive.

In [46]:
# sentiment for polarity
gta_ts_review['polarity'] = [TextBlob(text).sentiment[0] for text in gta_ts_review['text']]
In [47]:
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(6,10))

From the boxplot, I notice that the Tim Horton's has significantly smaller number for all quartiles and lower whisker than Starbucks and Second Cup. Starbucks and Second Cup have similar statistics.

I also calculate the proportion of positive reviews (polarity > 0) and the mean polarity of reviews for each coffee brand.

In [48]:
pos_ts = gta_ts_review.loc[gta_ts_review['polarity'] > 0]
len(pos_ts.loc[pos_ts['name'] == "Tims"]) / len(gta_ts_review.loc[gta_ts_review['name'] == "Tims"])
brands = ['Tims', 'Starbucks', 'second cup']
proportions = [len(pos_ts.loc[pos_ts['name'] == b]) / len(gta_ts_review.loc[gta_ts_review['name'] == b]) for b in brands]
means = [gta_ts_review.loc[gta_ts_review['name'] == b]['polarity'].mean() for b in brands]
temp = {"brand": brands, "proportion of positive reviews": proportions, "mean polarity of reviews": means}
display(Latex("\\begin{center}The proportion of positive reviews and the mean of polarity\\\ " + \
              pd.DataFrame(temp).to_latex(index=False) + \
              "\\end{center}"))
\begin{center}The proportion of positive reviews and the mean of polarity\\ \begin{tabular}{lrr} \toprule brand & proportion of positive reviews & mean polarity of reviews \\ \midrule Tims & 0.676982 & 0.098226 \\ Starbucks & 0.836054 & 0.179703 \\ second cup & 0.837740 & 0.188114 \\ \bottomrule \end{tabular} \end{center}

Again, Tim Horton's has lower proportion and mean than the other two brands. From all observed statistic above, I have enough evidence that Tim Hortons' reviews have more negative language than Starbucks' and Second Cup's reviews; Starbucks and Second Cup have similar languages in their reviews.

Conclusion¶

Generally, Yelp reviewers use different language in their reviews of GTA's Tim Horton's and Starbucks. Although some phrases are mentioned in both franchises' reviews, Starbucks customers tend to have more positive languages in their reviews than Tim Horton's customers.

Discussion and Further Research¶

Starbucks' and Second Cup's products often have high price tag than Tim Horton's product, and they have more positive reviews. Also, in question 4.3 I conclude that the business near the lake shore have high ratings, and we know that most luxurious business are located near the shore. Therefore, further research can be done on whether there is a positive relationship between business pricing and the review ratings / languages.
